### Description

When using TestBed.inject on a standalone component, there seem to be problems that TestBed.inject does not return the correctly injected service. 

Here is an example of the service:

```
@Component({
  selector: 'app-whatever',
  standalone: true,
  providers: [AlertService], // <-- Here is the problem
})
export class AppComponent {
  constructor(private alertService: AlertService) {}

  doSomething() {
    this.alertService.alert('I am working');
  }
}
```

We now want to to test if the service function was called, when the component does something:

```
const alertService = TestBed.inject(AlertService);
const alertSpy = spyOn(alertService, 'alert').and.stub();
component.doSomething();
expect(alertSpy).toHaveBeenCalled();
```

However this fails. When removing the providers array from the component metadata the test works but the application itself throws an error. A workaround is to get the service instance like this:

```const alertService = fixture.debugElement.injector.get(AlertService);```

